10-48. Under the figure osa conqueror leading home the Muses in triumph, Virgil proposes to celebrate Augustus in verse. In the ' following allegory the temple is the poem, Caesar its tutelar deity, the poet officiating as high priest. The sculptures and statues, representing the victories of Augustus and his royal line, are the subjects of the poem. Games and stage-plays were the usual ac- cessories of a triumph.
